.section-grouping
  %h2(id="get-template") a. Download an example template

  %p
    Retrieve an
    %a{ :href => "https://github.com/aeolusproject/aeolus-extras/raw/master/templates/fedora_14_x86_64.tpl",
        :title => "Example Fedora 14 template file" } example Fedora 14 template file
    (less than 1kb in size) from the Aeolus website: 

  %pre
    :preserve
      $ wget https://github.com/aeolusproject/aeolus-extras/raw/master/templates/fedora_14_x86_64.tpl

%br

.section-grouping
  %h2(id="build-image") b. Build an image using the template

  %p
    Images are created from templates using the <b>aeolus-image</b>
    command.

  %h3(id="build-ec2") Building for EC2

  %p
    The arguments used in the example below instruct it to create a new
    image, for EC2, from the template file we just downloaded:

  %pre
    :preserve
      $ sudo aeolus-image build --target ec2 --template fedora_14_x86_64.tpl
      Target Image: aeeab323-9992-4fde-b844-1a8b29660608
      Image: <span style="color: blue">512e4b0c-9f78-48b8-86f4-fd264dc76b53</span>
      Build: 59109a7a-4026-4129-b161-36a1e93b40d5
      Status: COMPLETED
      Percent Complete: 100

  %p
    EC2 image builds are very quick, as no significant work needs to be done
    locally.


  %h3(id="build-vsphere") Building for vSphere

  %p
    The arguments used in the example below instruct it to create a new
    image, for vSphere, from the template file downloaded above:

  %pre
    :preserve
      $ sudo aeolus-image build --target vsphere --template fedora_14_x86_64.tpl

      Target Image: 6403c4ca-cac8-4d80-ba7a-53b08b468023
      Image: <span style="color: blue">cc8abd98-ccff-4641-b386-e5d6ef13ba7e</span>
      Build: 7901ff4e-5b55-49fd-9207-f92d5dd5cb5c
      Status: New
      Percent Complete: <span style="color: red">0</span>

  %p
    Unlike builds for EC2, vSphere building is done locally.  This can take a
    significant amount of time.

  %p
    To avoid tying up a terminal session,
    %b aeolus-image
    launches vSphere builds as background processes.

  %p
    You will need to periodically query the progress of vSphere image
    builds, until they are complete.

%br

.section-grouping
  %h2(id="push-image") c. Push to a Provider Account

  %p
    The <b>aeolus-image</b> command is also used for pushing images to any
    configured Provider Account. 


  %h3(id="push-ec2") Pushing to EC2

  %b Push the image to Amazon EC2


  %h3(id="push-vsphere") Pushing to vSphere

  %b Push the image to the vSphere installation

  %pre
    :preserve
      $ sudo aeolus-image push --provider vsphere --id FOO


